Decrypting whatever is read is the difficulty I think, but NFC has it's own encryption standards, so i'm not sure if your private key on your wallet is being encrypted twice (once by being stored on the wallet, second for NFC transfer) or it's just doing one NFC encryption on it.

Totally, but the issue is that in this case is that its the encryption part that saves it and not access to the encrypted information (the key) which they purport is "unhackable because no usb port". Not at all correct.

One way to look at it is that NFC is just a standard communication protocol at a certain frequency range for all kinds of devices and tags. They make the app and end device, but also rely on this standard protocol used by everyone. If you look at the security section in wiki for nfc, they list hypothetical attacks.
